  "text": "Using an approximation of the integral operator in (24), we provide analytical evidence that the new type of traveling waves with z > 0 bifurcate from the Atkinson-Cabrera solution precisely at the threshold velocity V 0 , below which the latter becomes inadmissible. To begin with, note that in view of (22) we have q(ξ) = −U ′ (ξ), where U(ξ) is the Atkinson-Cabrera solution, which, as we recall, is of class C 1 at ξ = 0 and C 2 elsewhere. On the other hand, the admissibility conditions (7) for U clearly imply that U ′ (0) ≤ 0. Hence, a sufficient condition for loss of admissibility is q(0) < 0. Computing q(0) as a function of V numerically from (22), we see in Fig. 3a that it is monotone increasing and changes signs at a single velocity V 0 . Consequently, the Atkinson-Cabrera solution is inadmissible at velocities below V 0 . This argument does not in fact prove that it is admissible above V 0 , but the numerical results for U(ξ) at various velocities confirm that this is the case; see also [CITATION_1] . The conclusion is: The velocity V 0 at which q(0) changes signs is the threshold velocity below which the Atkinson-Cabrera solution becomes inadmissible.",
